Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of the turnover tax of the Czech Republic and Germany
Preface
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the accounting offices are empowered to audit all public finances.
The statement requires that the accounting firms have the power to consider the tax collection as much as possible.
The Organisation of European Top Accounting Authorities (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be a significant part of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the VI. EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, formed the audit of public revenue by the accounting offices.
One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit activities of a Court of Auditors is the development of a specific strategy for the audit of public revenue.
This is especially true of taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.
As national economies are increasingly linked and dependent on each other, there may be a situation where national accounting firms can carry out their audit activities only in cooperation with other states' accounting offices.
As an example, testing of internationally organized fraud can be considered, which can lead to significant loss of revenue in many states.
Cooperation between authorities is needed in the fight against such offences.
Accounting firms that examine this area must be prepared to cooperate closely with each other.
The idea of an audit of the sales tax as well as the MIAS system is with the VI. EUROSAI Congress in Bonn was created. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Court of Auditors.
In the course of a thorough preparation, the participating accounting offices first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures of the sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and in Germany.
Due to the evaluation of the available information, we selected the test items for the test planning.
Achieving sound and effective management of sales tax is a long-standing problem and individual States (in particular the EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, to simplify the collection of turnover tax and to create greater transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit can not only help improve the work of financial management, but also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.
