The period under review covered the period 1. May 2004 until 31. December 2005.
Summary of results and evaluation of the parallel audit
The parallel audit of the sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two accounting offices.
In addition to the focus on exchange of information under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation 1925/2004, other closely related aspects have also been examined, including: For example, registration of tax securities, tax returns and summary messages.
In addition, the test also extended to the legal situation in cross-border passenger transport by bus and to the comparison of statistical data.
When comparing the systems of sales tax administrations in the two States, differences were noted in the following areas:
1) Registration for sales tax purposes.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the level of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the essential criterion for registration is to exceed the turnover threshold laid down in the Sales Tax Act.
In the Czech Republic, the taxable persons only receive a single tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, the tax payer receives a tax number only applicable to domestic transactions for the purposes of sales tax.
If the German tax payer wishes to carry out significant intra-Community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called USt-IDNo., to be issued.
As problems arise from the different registration procedures, the rules within the EC should be harmonised (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport by bus.
In the Czech Republic, cross-border passenger transport by bus is duty-free, but there is a right to deduct the advance tax.
In Germany, the transport power, as far as the route passes through Germany, is subject to sales tax.
Efforts should be made at EC level, the situation referred to in Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28. To unify with the Common System of Turnover Tax (see 4.2) on 1 November 2006.
3) Tax returns.
While in the Czech Republic the tax-payer tax returns must only be made for under-year tax periods (month or quarter), tax-payer in Germany (monthly or quarterly)
Advance sales tax declarations and a annual revenue tax return after the end of the calendar year.
Unlike the Czech Republic, tax-payer companies in Germany must submit pre-tax statements by electronic means.
The introduction of the PTO in the Czech Republic would improve the incidence of the Czech financial administration (see 4.3).
4) Summary messages.
While tax agents in the Czech Republic are required to submit their summary notifications to the Financial Offices (CMO), German tax agents are required to submit summary notifications to CLO2.
Accordingly, in the Czech Republic, the information from the Summary Notifications is available to the Federal Republic immediately after they have been submitted.
The information from the Summary Reports is only available after their processing by the CLO.
In order to combat turnover tax fraud, updated information on intra-Community transactions is needed as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of Summary Messages would shorten the period between the time of sales and the updating of MIAS data.
This would allow for a timely examination of taxation in the buyer's Member State (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same deadlines.
5) International exchange of information in the field of turnover tax.
In the event of incoming requests for information, the Czech CLO shall monitor compliance with the three-month period.
The German CLO does not monitor the processing times.
As a result, the German Financial Administration has made a significantly lower percentage of requests for information within the specified time limit.
Because of these problems, the BRH recommended that the German CLO be constantly monitored (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each Member State shall develop its own risk management system (RMS) with appropriate strengths and weaknesses.
The NKÚ and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EC Member States. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5).
As part of the cooperation, the two accounting offices examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions realized between Czech and German tax objects.
Of these, 31 cases were jointly reviewed by taking advantage of CLO's legal possibilities, in which there were doubts about the correct taxation or suspicion of turnover tax fraud.
The Court of Auditors found that:
In some cases, the CMO used the information obtained in the international exchange of information and re-established the VAT liability of the taxable persons concerned.
In these cases, the taxable persons had either unlawfully used the VAT exemption or failed to identify the purchase of goods in their sales tax return.
In some cases, the CMO could not use the information obtained in the exchange of information because they were incomplete or incomplete.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal provisions in the two Member States.
In some cases, the financial management of another Member State refused the requested information.
A number of cases were uncovered where taxable persons in their summary reported transactions incorrectly.
As a result, the data in the MIAS were accordingly faulty, so that in these cases the employees (the CMO) had to determine (see 6).
