Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two states varies.
While entrepreneurs are registered in Germany regardless of the level of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is the excess of the threshold amount referred to in the Sales Tax Act.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he or she may voluntarily register.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardized, but differences can occur due to different organizational structures in the various federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the tax payer will receive a tax number at the time of his first registration for any tax.
In the event of its registration for sales tax, this tax number shall also apply to intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who can register for sales tax purposes will receive a tax number exclusively for domestic German transactions.
If the German entrepreneur wishes to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must specifically assign a VAT ID No. apply.
Both the NKÚ and the BRH found that the German two-stage registration system in other Member States such as the Czech Republic, which awards a single identification number for both national registration for sales tax and intra-Community transactions, could lead to significant misconceptions.
On the other hand, the two-tier system allows retroactive (national registration) in cases where the taxpayer does not declare his business to the municipality or to the competent FA.
This retroactive registration allows for a sufficient estimate of the VAT on turnover for previous periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the tax liability.
Since the different registration procedures lead to problems, the rules for the whole EC should be harmonised.
The German Parliament recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be assigned by the Federal Central Office for Taxes to each natural person after birth.
This number applies to natural persons resident in Germany for life.
Where a natural person enters into business, the competent FA shall apply for a commercial tax identification number as UST ID No. serves.
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the national registration of a tax payer and the allocation of the USt ID No. give.
Work to implement an IT process for managing the numbers has not yet been completed.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus
Legal provisions in the Czech Republic
According to the provisions of section 70 of Law No 235/2004, since 1. May, 2004 the transportation from passengers between the single member states as well as between the member states and third countries in Czech Republic of the sales tax releases and there is claim to pretax deduction.
The exemption from turnover tax shall also apply where the transport of persons registered as persons liable for tax in Member States other than Member States is carried out by foreigners who are liable for tax.
The return journey is considered a separate transport operation.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not carry out any economic activity other than cross-border passenger transport by bus, they shall not be allowed to register in the Czech Republic as having effect on turnover tax.
Cross-border passenger transport was exempted from the VAT weight in the Czech Republic under the Law of Accession of the Czech Republic, Annex V, Chapter 5 (1) (b). The referring body is worded as follows:
'For the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77/388/EEC, the Czech Republic may, in accordance with point 17 of Annex F to the Directive, maintain the exemption for cross-border carriage of persons, either until the condition laid down in Article 28 (4) of the Directive is met or for as long as the same exemption is applied by any of the present Member States'.
The legal regulations in Germany
In accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28. November 2006, as implemented in Germany by Section 3b (1) of the UStG, a transport performance is carried out where the transport is carried out.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the domestic portion of the transport power is taxable in Germany.
Nor does German taxation distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident person carries tax persons through Germany, the part of the transport in Germany shall be regarded as a taxable person.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident contractor must report his intention to provide passenger transport services to the competent FA.
The latter shall register it for tax purposes (compare 4.1.2) and shall issue a special certificate for each motor bus mentioned in the declaration of the taxable person.
The entrepreneur must state his tax-bearing transport services in a German sales tax return.
1. March 2006, there were 741 Czech bus contractors registered with the FA both in Germany and in the South of Germany.
If the transport performance is provided to a domestic resident, the non-resident tax payer does not have to pay the sales tax himself to the FA.
In its place, the domestic buyer of the services must pay the turnover tax to the tax office and the net amount charged to the non-resident tax payer. This operation is referred to as the 'relocation of the tax liability partnership' and is in accordance with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC.
In addition to being notified by a non-resident tax payer and his income tax return, the German Financial Administration has several means of examining the accuracy of the tax return with regard to taxable persons' promotions:
Mobile control groups of the customs check the certificates of motor buses registered abroad, which are used for passenger transport through Germany.
After each test, the mobile control groups shall send an inspection report to the competent FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group may require the bus driver to pay the sales tax before continuing his journey.
The non-resident tax payer may deduct the turnover tax thus paid from the tax liability indicated in his sales tax return.
If the FA has doubts about the correctness of a sales tax return, it may order an audit which has taken place in the FA, or may use the means of assistance referred to in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign taxpayer refuses to pay the lawfully fixed sales tax, the FA may request assistance under Council Directive 76/308/EEC.
The BRH considers these means of administrative assistance in tax matters to be too expensive for a non-resident bus operator to verify the VAT return or compliance with the tax weight of a non-resident bus operator in relation to the low level of revenue tax on tax-related passenger transport.
In particular, checking the books of a non-resident taxpayer causes disproportionately high costs to the taxpayer himself and to the financial administration.
The latter must examine the foreign books, for which it is necessary not only to know the foreign language but also the foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an audit is expected to have a higher amount of time than that of a resident tax payer, although the test is limited to passenger transport in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxpayer must not only exercise the audit rights of his national financial management, but also those of the other Member States, in so far as he carries out the promotion of persons there.
In addition, for each Member State where only one person is carried out, the taxable person must comply with all existing tax obligations in the different languages and on the basis of the forms of the financial administrations of the EC Member States concerned.
This means that the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services will result in a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation varies in the two states.
In the Czech Republic, promotion of persons between different EC Member States and between Member States and third countries is exempt from turnover tax under the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the transport performance is subject to sales tax in accordance with the German national transport route.
If a non-resident taxpayer provides such a transport performance for the first time, he must notify the competent FA thereof in advance.
This records the tax payer who must declare the tax-bearing share of the transport performance in a tax return in Germany.
The law enforcement in Germany is very time consuming.
At least three out of four Czech tax agents registered with the FA in the West of Germany have passenger transport as a business purpose.
The amount of tax in question is quite low in relation to the administrative burden.
Member States - which 46 the turnover tax referred to in Article 28 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC. 7 November 2006 on the common system of turnover tax - have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant tax volume.
In order to avoid the disproportionate costs of the VAT incentive, cross-border passenger transport should only be subject to tax liability in one Member State.
This could be the state where the promotion begins or where the service provider is based.
Such a type of taxation would amend Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28. On November 2006.
Sales tax explanations
Filing and processing of sales tax returns in the Czech Republic
Unless otherwise provided by the Law, the trader shall be entitled to pay a sales tax return on the form laid down by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the expiry of the tax period, even if no tax liability has been incurred.
The tax liability shall be incurred at the end of the period for the submission of the sales tax return. In accordance with Law No 235/2004, the VAT on imports of goods is excluded from this scheme. Here, the maturity of the tax is determined in accordance with the customs rules.
Where above-average deductible advance taxes result in a refund claim, that amount shall be refunded to the taxable person within 30 days of the date of the fixing of that deduction without the need to draw up an application for this purpose.
The period shall not be applied in cases where the financial officer initiates a tax procedure relating to the taxable person's tax liability.
According to Paragraph 73 (11) of Law No 235/2004, the right to deduct VAT may be invoked at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year during which the right to deduct was established.
After the expiry of this period, the deduction may be relied upon within three years of the end of the tax period during which the application would have been possible for the first time.
