The need to set up the special audit units arose from the increase in established new and "improved" forms of tax evasion particularly related to chain shops.
These specific units shall check in accordance with the requirements of the tax agencies or shall focus on taxable persons with certain activities, multinational companies and tax persons with particularly high turnover.
The following mechanisms for reducing the risks of turnover tax have been integrated into the ATIS system: - The task of 'the credibility of sales tax returns' to assess the risk of deduced tax returns, - the task of 'selecting the taxable persons to be audited', with the selection of the taxable persons to be audited on the basis of certain criteria, the task of 'MIAS', which allows financial officers to access the data provided by the other EC Member States.
The "MIAS" task allows, among other things: - Verification of the validity of the USt ID No. Of taxable persons from other Member States, - confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech taxable person, as indicated in the ZM by all suppliers of the taxable persons concerned from other Member States, - Preparation of a list of taxable persons who have not supplied ZM - Formal control of the data supplied in the ZM by all suppliers of the taxable persons in the other Member States which have failed to supply VAT in their Member States, prior to the non-dumping list, before the non-dumping of which Czech States have failed to the non-dumped VAT data are transferred to the non-dumping data in the Czech.
As part of their perception of duties to combat tax evasion, financial officers have access to the data from state authorities such as trade registers, Land Registry, Motor Vehicle Records, Rifle Register, etc.
