Risk management in Germany
Due to their federal construction in the Federal Republic of Germany, both the Federal Insurance Authorities (particularly the CLO) and the financial administrations of the 16 Federal States are involved in the development and introduction of an RMS.
While there are common working groups for development, neither the CLO nor the financial administrations of the Federal States fully have a single data base.
At CLO level, Unit ST I 2 (hereinafter referred to as' CUSS '- Coordination Body for Turnover Tax Special Audits and Tax Enforcement Measures) collects audit findings on fraud cases in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called ZAUBER was established at the KUSS. There, financial offices can enter and also query the names of discovered missing traders or revenue tax agents.
The KUSS coordinates both related cases of sales tax fraud at national level and cases of cross-border sales tax fraud.
The experience of the KUSS will be introduced into the development of the RMS through its cooperation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organizational units of the CLO and BMF are also involved.
Formal verification of the composition of UStIdNr. Other Member States appearing in the ZM of German tax payer shall be carried out by the CLO.
This formal review is carried out before the transmission of the ZM to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the MIAS data and thus its benefits (see 4.4.2).
Verification of validity in the ZM named USt ID No. Is based on the O _ MCTL identifiers submitted by the other Member States (for the purpose of correcting invalid UST No., see also 4.4.2).
In addition, the CLO's RMS is based on the MIAS data transmitted by the other Member States and generates various types of communications for the discovery of suspected missing traders. As indications, certain features are used, usually occurring in carousel stores.
The Federal Police of the Federal States are dependent on the processing of these communications and have the result of their investigation in certain cases to be forwarded to the CLO.
The BRH's audit has confirmed that all available features need to be included to close with sufficient likelihood of a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the BRH recommended the BMF to work with combinations of different signs in the preparation of the communications.
The risk management system should also take into account other indications, such as: For example, the payment behaviour of the taxable person, the industry or the interests of the company.
A second level of risk management exists with the financial administrations of the Federal States and focuses on the processing of turnover tax advances and annual declarations.
For example, to create the system For example, a list of those taxable persons who have indicated intra-Community deliveries in their sales tax advance or annual declaration.
This list is sent to the CLO in order to monitor the complete delivery of ZM.
Furthermore, in this type of risk management, the acquisition stated by the tax payer in his annual sales tax return is compared with the data in the MIAS.
The financial administrations of the Federal States avoid comparing quarterly data as these would result in too many inconsistencies due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; z. B.:
- Suppliers and acquirers shall assume different dates for the execution of intra-Community turnover;
- Different accounting records and tax declarations of skonti and discounts.
In addition to comparing the data from the sales tax declarations with the MIAS data, many municipalities have certain risk management mechanisms based on information contained in the sales tax returns and certain other indications (e.g. company terms, age of holders/shareholders, number of employees and method of payment of the tax payer).
Bavaria has introduced a fixed-rules risk management system that allows a team of anti-tax fraud specialists (hereinafter referred to as "risk managers") to programme their own rules in such a way as to eliminate suspected tax agents.
This system is used in the processing of the VAT declarations by the German Federal Police Office.
As a result, the competent FA receives the information provided by the RMS before the sales tax is set.
Since this system is not learner, risk managers must adapt the rules according to feedback from the CMO.
Mecklenburg-Western Germany has developed an adaptive neuronal network based on the data of uncovered lagging cases.
Because of this data, the RMS is capable of learning the characteristics for tax evasion.
The system creates a monthly list of tax cases where there is evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent CMO shall decide on the examination of the taxable persons concerned.
After the audit, tax auditors must report their results, allowing the RMS to learn from the results of the audits it proposes.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neuronal network is used in combination with a rule-based fuzzy system.
Based on many data from edited sales tax returns and some other evidence, this neuro-fuzzy system (also called datamining system) calculates how likely a tax payer is to be engulfed in tax fraud.
After that, it creates a monthly list of alleged tax agents.
On the basis of this list, the CMO shall select the taxable persons concerned for verification and report the audit results to the data center concerned.
The introduction of these three RMS is underway in the federal states.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems appears to be targeted.
Whether the expected effects will be adjusted during actual use remains to be seen.
Comparison and evaluation
Although the present report does not allow the specific criteria of the RMS to be addressed in Czech and Germany, the NKÚ and the BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three German Länder mentioned above, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border sales tax fraud.
Sales tax fraud - particularly carousel fraud - has proved to be not a national but a European problem.
The persons involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one Member State but in several Member States.
A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State. If this is not done, fraudsters seek out the Member State with the weakest RMS for their offences.
The tax breaks caused by pan-European fraud in sales taxes do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the company is established.
Any other Member State involved in the fraud may be affected.
This is why there should be a European exchange of experience on the RMS.
