By request from the local Czech financial officer, the NKÚ found that, after receiving the reply from Germany, the latter had reached out to the accountant of the Czech tax payer and had stayed with her in such a way that she wanted to discuss the submission of a supplementary sales tax return for the third quarter of 2004, after reviewing the invoices together with the company owner.
So far no supplementary sales tax return has been made.
The Czech Financial Officer informed the NKÚ that he would proceed in such a way as to ensure that the time limits for retroactive tax fixing for the tax period concerned were maintained.
17.
In the fourth quarter of 2004, the German tax payer delivered €11,600 worth of goods to the German tax payer.
As part of the intergovernmental exchange of information, the German financial officer requested a review of whether the Czech tax payer actually existed, since the alleged investor of the German tax payer had established a number of headlong flows in Germany.
In the course of the FA's review of the transaction, the Czech tax payer confirmed the acquisition of the goods.
However, according to the Czech tax dividend, the goods were not delivered from Germany to the Czech Republic but were resold in Germany in 2005.
The Czech tax payer submitted supporting documents for the sale in January 2005.
The Czech payer was not registered in Germany as having effect on sales tax and had not taxed the sale of the product in question either in the Czech Republic or in Germany.
All of these facts pointed to tax evasion within Germany and the Czech financial officer provided this information in his reply to the request for information to the German financial administration.
By request from the local Czech financial officer, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax payer had issued a supplementary tax return for the fourth quarter of 2004 in which he declared, among other things, the value of the goods he had acquired from a German tax payer while claiming the right to deduct VAT from other Member States.
In his Czech sales tax statement, he did not apply for sales tax on the sale of goods in Germany.
Due to a supplementary sales tax return issued after the expiry audit, the Czech financial officer set the turnover tax liability unchanged.
According to Czech legislation, there was no acquisition of goods from other Member States in this case, since the goods were not dispatched or transported from another Member State to the Czech Republic.
Thus, the Czech financial officer reached a wrong conclusion in the external audit.
The BRH found that immediately after receiving the reply to the request for information, which indicated that the goods had not left Germany, the German financial officer corrected the German tax payer's tax return and called for the payment of sales tax worth €1,600.
In addition, the competent FA sent a control notification to the FA responsible for the actual consignee of the goods in order to ensure that the resale of these goods is properly taxed.
