18.
The Czech financial officer received a request for information from the German Financial Administration on whether the Czech tax payer acquired a car worth €47,400 from the German tax payer in February 2005.
The request for information was accompanied, as an annex, by a copy of the Czech tax payer's sales tax registration certificate.
As a further appendix, a photocopy of the passport was attached to the person who was supposed to have transferred the vehicle.
In the course of his investigation, the Czech finance official found that the passport was stolen, that the person named therein had not introduced a vehicle to the Czech Republic and claimed it had no contacts with a German tax payer.
The sales tax registration certificate, the print of which had been sent by the German side, had not been issued by the Czech Financial Administration.
By providing such information, the Czech financial officer replied to the request for information while stating that he could not confirm the acquisition of the car.
By request from the local Czech financial officer, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax agent is not based at the address indicated in the trade register and that the managing director of the company is unreachable.
Following a tax liability procedure for the tax period February 2005, the Czech financial officer set the Czech tax payer's tax liability at zero.
In the course of a further investigation, the Czech finance official found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had acquired it on the basis of an Internet ad.
The BRH found that the local German financial officer had rejected the German tax payer's claim to exemption from sales tax on the basis of the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an expiry review, a German FA was unable to clarify a difference of €3,000 between the value of the goods purchased in the sales tax return and the reported values from other Member States.
