As part of the parallel examination, the NKÚ, in cooperation with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community supplies between the Czech Republic and Germany, which were not the subject of a prior exchange of information between the two countries.
The two accounting offices exchanged information about the cases under consideration through the CLO of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not established in Germany, informed the competent FA of its intention to make taxable transactions in Germany.
Due to this information, the company was registered as of June 2005, but did not receive German USt-IDNr.
The (UCR) accepted a contract from a Danish company (UDK) for the production of wind turbines and for their delivery to Austria on behalf, on the risk and on behalf of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient production capacity, the Danish company transferred part of the contract to a German tax payer (UDE) in Germany.
The following figure represents the contractual relations and transport route of wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
- The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines to Austria on its behalf, at its risk and for its own bill for assembly.
Due to the assembly, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the supply of wind turbines is taxable in Austria.
- Because the shipper was commissioned by the Danish company (UDK) and the latter had the transport carried out on its own behalf, at its own risk and on its own account, the delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE) is where the transport started, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the recipient is registered as taxable persons in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the delivery of the German Sub-Contractor (UDE), since the EC Member State for which the supply was intended is a different 19 than the State of residence of the Czech undertaking.
Accordingly, die- se delivery is properly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its sales tax returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on the place where the transport began.
However, transport was carried out on some of the wind turbines from the Czech Republic and on others from Germany.
- The supply of wind turbines manufactured in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
- The supply of the remaining wind turbines produced in Germany took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) provided both intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-Community deliveries from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare intra-Community supplies in its German tax returns or in its ZM delivered to the German CLO.
Thus, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community supplies uniformly as intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic.
The NKÚ found that (UCR) did not report intra-Community deliveries to Austria but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, cooperation between at least four financial administrations (the Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be necessary, although there is no evidence of tax fraud or evasion in this case.
In addition, the NKÚ and BRH examined case sizes to show the size of the differences between the data contained in the sales tax returns and MIAS data caused by the different 2004 legislation.
The cases under consideration also show that it takes some time for the tax authorities to apply the new legal provisions:
22. In its ZM for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech tax payer reported a total value of CZK 792.977.452 to a German tax payer.
During the same period, another Czech tax payer reported intra-Community supplies in his ZM to another German tax payer in the total value of CZK 18.157,265.
The information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ showed that these were electricity supplies in both cases.
Both Czech taxpayers took into account the abovementioned deliveries in their ZM in accordance with Czech Law No 235/2004 in force in 2004.
In a further examination of these transactions, an audit group of the NKÚ found that in 2004 different statutory provisions on the supply or purchase of electrical energy between the Czech Republic and Germany applied.
While in the Czech Republic, the tax credits weigh the supplies of electric energy in accordance with the voting of Law No. 235/2004 declared intra-Community deliveries of goods, according to the German legal provisions in force in 2004, it was not an intra-Community acquisition of goods but taxable and taxable transactions in Germany.
The differences in legal provisions were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Law No 635/2004, which 1 effective as of. January 2005, some tax provisions amended.
23. When examining intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further established that a Czech tax payer in his ZM for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 declared intra-Community supplies to a German tax payer in the total value of CZK 240.411,163 and another Czech tax payer in his ZM of 4,476 for the same period.
Information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ showed that in both cases these were supplies of electrical energy.
According to the text of the from 1. Law No 235/2004 in force on January 1, 2005, where electrical energy is supplied, the place of performance shall be the place where the acquirer has his legal place of business, place of business or place of business for which that supply is made.
Therefore, the Czech taxpayers should not have indicated the electricity supplies in their ZM for 2005.
The fact that both tax agents treated the supply of electrical energy in their ZM as intra-Community supplies led to a fair difference of CZK 503.881.939 in MIAS.
Concluding remark
The cooperation achieved the objectives of the BRH and the NKÚ.
Both accounting offices gained in-depth knowledge of the systems of sales tax administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the legal rules applicable to sales tax management.
During the parallel tests, interesting cases of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions came to light.
For some of these, another observation is worth watching.
On the basis of the audit results, both audit firms made recommendations for managing sales tax.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a control review should be part of the further observation.
The new experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation of both accounting offices is the basis for the successful implementation of future audits in the field of turnover tax management.
